RMP Report for Cape Canaveral Air Force Station

Executive Summary

This RMP update executive summary is organized to comply with EPA RMP definitions and requirements to include the following:

Introduction
CCAFS policies to protect the environment, health and safety of people;
Facility identification and regulated substances covered processes;
Prevention Program;
Planned updates;
Five-year accident history;
Emergency Response Plan; and
Planned changes to safety.

Introduction

40 Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) 68 mandates the development and implementation of a Risk Management Plan for facilities that manufacture, use, or store any of the toxic and flamable substances listed in 40 CFR 68.130.  A Risk Management Plan (RMP) is in effect at Cape Canaveral Air Force Station (CCAFS) for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials.  This document is a RMP update to verify the facts set forth in the orginal RMP and to advise the 45th Space wing if they are not correct and compliant with 40 CFR 68.

CCAFS policies to protect the environment, health and safety of people

CCAFS has numerous plans in place for the protection of the environment such as the Spill Prevention Control and Countermeasure (SPCC) Plan.  CCAFS also has emergency response plans in place for the protection and safety of people.  CCAFS emergency response plans have recently been changed and updated concerning the protection of the health and safety of the people working at CCAFS and the populous surrounding CCAFS.  Moreover, the RMP assists in the protection of the CCAFS community and the surrounding population.  These plans give specific and detailed directions of the actions to be taken by different organizations to protect the health and safety of CCAFS personnel, the public, and the environment. There are several response plans in place at CCAFS and Kennedy Space Center.  The following are examples of such documents:

